: A People’s History, North of 60, and coverage of the funeral of Pierre Trudeau reveal how television works to resolve the imagined community of nation, as well as the idea of a national self and national others, via affect. Affect theory, with its notions of changeability, fluidity, and contagion, is, the author argues, well suited to the study of television and its audience. Useful for scholars and students of media studies, communications theory, and national television and for anyone interested in Canadian popular culture, this highly readable book fills the need for critical scholarly analysis of Canadian television’s nationalist practices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadians. 0aNational characteristics, CanadianxCanada. 0aNational characteristics, Canadian. 0aTelevision and politicsxCanada. 0aTelevision and politicszCanada. 0aTelevision broadcastingxPsychological aspectsxCanada. 0aTelevision broadcastingxSocial aspectsxCanada. 0aTelevision broadcastingxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aTelevisionzCanadaxPsychological aspects. 4aCultural Studies. 4aFilm & Media. 4aPolitical Science. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721940uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978155458308940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781554583089423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781554583089/original  a978-3-11-127414-0  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010c2010d2011  aGBV-deGruyter-alles